✅ 1. operator: In
Means the label must match one of the values.

matchExpressions:
- key: app
  operator: In
  values: ["web", "api"]
✔ Matches:
	• app=web
	• app=api
❌ Does NOT match:
	• app=db
	• app=test
	• label missing

❌ 2. operator: NotIn
Means the label must NOT match any value in the list.

matchExpressions:
- key: app
  operator: NotIn
  values: ["db", "cache"]
✔ Matches:
	• app=web
	• app=api
	• app=frontend
❌ Does NOT match:
	• app=db
	• app=cache

🟢 3. operator: Exists
Means the label key must exist, value does not matter.

matchExpressions:
- key: region
  operator: Exists
✔ Matches:
	• region=us
	• region=eu
	• region=india
❌ Does NOT match:
	• label not present on node or pod

🔴 4. operator: DoesNotExist
The label key must NOT exist.

matchExpressions:
- key: region
  operator: DoesNotExist
✔ Matches:
	• nodes/pods without a region label
❌ Does NOT match:
	• If region label exists at all

🔼 5. operator: Gt (Greater Than)
Used for numeric comparison.

matchExpressions:
- key: cpu
  operator: Gt
  values: ["4"]
✔ Matches: cpu=5, cpu=8, cpu=10
❌ Does NOT match: cpu=4, cpu=2
	Value must be stored as a string, but Kubernetes treats it as number.

🔽 6. operator: Lt (Less Than)
Label value must be less than given value.

matchExpressions:
- key: memory
  operator: Lt
  values: ["16"]
✔ Matches: memory=8, memory=12
❌ Does NOT match: memory=16, memory=32

⭐ SUPER SIMPLE RECAP
Operator	Meaning
In	value must be inside list
NotIn	value must NOT be inside list
Exists	label key must exist
DoesNotExist	label key must NOT exist
Gt	label value > X
Lt	label value < X

🔥 Real Examples from Exam
Example 1 — Pod must go only to nodes with env=prod or env=stage

matchExpressions:
- key: env
  operator: In
  values: ["prod", "stage"]
Example 2 — Pod must run only on nodes WITHOUT GPU

operator: DoesNotExist
Example 3 — Node must have more than 4 CPUs

operator: Gt
values: ["4"]






