🟦 OPTION 1 — Create Your Own Kubernetes Cluster on EC2 (Using kubeadm)
This is the BEST “real-world” alternative to EKS and is often used in interviews.
✔ What you do:
You will:
	• Launch 2 or 3 EC2 instances
	• Install Docker
	• Install Kubernetes (kubeadm, kubelet, kubectl)
	• Create your own cluster
	• Deploy your app (pod + service + deployment)
	• Install MySQL or MongoDB inside the cluster
✔ This becomes a FULL DevOps project without EKS.

🔥 Step-by-Step (Short Version)
1️⃣ Create 2 EC2 Ubuntu servers
	• 1 master node
	• 1 worker node
Open ports:
	• 6443
	• 10250
	• 30000–32767
	• SSH (22)

2️⃣ Install Docker

sudo apt update
sudo apt install docker.io -y

3️⃣ Install Kubernetes Components

sudo apt install -y apt-transport-https curl
sudo curl -s https://packages.cloud.google.com/apt/doc/apt-key.gpg | apt-key add -
echo "deb https://apt.kubernetes.io/ kubernetes-xenial main" | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/kubernetes.list
sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y kubeadm kubelet kubectl

4️⃣ Initialize Kubernetes Master

sudo kubeadm init
Copy the output:

kubeadm join <master-ip>:6443 --token ... --discovery-token-ca-cert-hash sha256:...

5️⃣ Configure kubectl

mkdir -p $HOME/.kube
sudo cp -i /etc/kubernetes/admin.conf $HOME/.kube/config
sudo chown $(id -u):$(id -g) $HOME/.kube/config

6️⃣ Install Network Add-on (Calico)

kubectl apply -f https://docs.projectcalico.org/manifests/calico.yaml

7️⃣ Join Worker Node
On worker EC2:

sudo kubeadm join <master-ip>:6443 --token .....

8️⃣ Deploy Your Application
Just apply like before:

kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
kubectl apply -f service.yaml

9️⃣ Deploy MySQL/MongoDB in the cluster
You can use:
MySQL YAML

kubectl apply -f mysql-deployment.yaml
or
MongoDB via Helm

helm install mongo bitnami/mongodb

